    "narrative": "For the April 22 slate, **James Wood** (76.28) and **Mickey Moniak** (75.98) headline our optimal lineup, as both benefit from elite matchup conditions against weak arms. **James Wood** finds a prime spot atop the order against Didier Fuentes, where the combination of a favorable park and a significant SP skill advantage (+19%) drives his high floor. Meanwhile, **Mickey Moniak** is in an ideal position against Walker Buehler; the projection accounts for a 14% park boost and Buehler\u2019s slow delivery to the plate, which historically inflates the stolen base ceiling\u2014a critical factor for us. **Vinnie Pasquantino** (68.43) also provides high value today, bolstered by a +14% platoon edge against Chris Bassitt and a helpful wind direction providing an extra +5% boost.\n\nThe most difficult roster decision today involves **Kyle Karros**, whose 62.00 score was the highest of our reserves. Despite projecting well against Walker Buehler, he was narrowly squeezed out of the starting lineup in favor of our established positional depth. The optimizer favored **Jose Caballero** (61.91) and **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (53.84) to maintain our aggressive stolen base profile, even though both face a tough matchup against Ranger Suarez. While **Kyle Karros** offered better raw efficiency than **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, the heavy weighting toward SB-capable hitters in a 5x5 Roto format keeps the latter in the mix despite his platoon disadvantage.\n\nManagers must remain vigilant as all listed projections are based on \"Lineup Pending\" status; if **Luis Campusano** or **Dalton Rushing** are shuffled to the bottom of their respective orders, their efficiency scores will slide toward the marginal threshold. Additionally, **Corbin Carroll** remains a start at 53.11, but his matchup against Anthony Kay is the most high-risk spot on the card; the elite SP skill suppression (-19%) and unfavorable platoon make him a candidate for a sub-par performance, even if his speed keeps him in the daily rotation.",
